Utility Classes and Functions
[Support Kit]

Detailed Description

Reference counting, data containers, and other tools.

anonymous enum
 

Special bits in the SSharedBuffer user count and length fields.

Note that these magic values are the LOW bits. This is to help code generation of THUMB instructions. It means that retrieving the real value requires a shift instead of a mask.

Enumerator:
B_BUFFER_USERS_SHIFT  Amount by which to shift user count.
B_BUFFER_LENGTH_SHIFT  Amount by which to shift length.
B_STATIC_USERS  Flag indicating SSharedBuffer is in the static text section of an executable.

This is part of the reference count of the shared memory buffer.

B_POOLED_USERS  Flag indicating SSharedBuffer is in the buffer pool.

This is part of the reference count of the shared memory buffer.

B_EXTENDED_BUFFER  Flag indicating SSharedBuffer has additional meta-data before the buffer.

This is part of the length of the shared memory buffer.

enum general_error_codes_enum
 

General error codes.

Enumerator:
B_NO_MEMORY 
B_BAD_VALUE  This error means that the given parameters made no sense. You will usually want to use a more specific error code than this such as sysErrBadIndex, sysErrBadType, sysErrMismatchedValues, or sysErrBadData.
B_NOT_ALLOWED  Generally you should use the more specific errors sysErrUnsupported or sysErrPermissionDenied.
B_TIMED_OUT 
B_BAD_INDEX 
B_BAD_TYPE 
B_MISMATCHED_VALUES 
B_NAME_NOT_FOUND  This error indicates that a plain name lookup did not succeed. You should use instead sysErrEntryNotFound for a lookup failure on a filesystem or other structured storage.
B_NAME_IN_USE  This error indicates that there is already a plain item with the requested name. You should use instead sysErrEntryExists for a name that already exists on a filesystem or other structured storage.
B_CANCELED 
B_NO_INIT  An operation on object could not be completed because that object has not been initialized. This error should only be returned when an object needs something besides just construction to be initialized. If initializion was attempted but could not be done, another more specific error should be returned.
B_PERMISSION_DENIED  This error specifically indicates that the requested operation is possible, you simply aren't to do it. Compare with sysErrEntryNotFound (the thing being operated on does not exist) and sysErrUnsupported (nobody can do what is being asked).
B_BAD_DATA  This indicates that the contents of structured input data is corrupt. It is used when the parameters are valid (unlike sysErrParamErr and friends), but the data they reference is bad. For example, calling a function to read a PNG image, where the image data is corrupt.
B_DATA_TRUNCATED  Some data was returned, but it is not all that was available and/or expected.
B_UNSUPPORTED  The implementation you are calling on does not support what was asked. Compare with sysErrPermissionDenied.
B_WOULD_BLOCK 
B_BUSY 
B_IO_ERROR  Very generic input/output error. Generally shouldn't be used, instead preferring more specific errors such as sysErrTimeout, sysErrCancelled, sysErrPermissionDenied, sysErrBrokenPipe, sysErrWouldBlock, sysErrBusy, sysErrInterrupted, etc.
B_DONT_DO_THAT 
B_BAD_DESIGN_ENCOUNTERED 
B_WEAK_REF_GONE 
B_END_OF_DATA  This is a pseudo-error, returned by iterators and other things that let you step through there data. It is returned when requesting more data when you have reached the end of the iterator.
B_INTERRUPTED 
B_BROKEN_PIPE 
B_ENTRY_NOT_FOUND  For example, trying to open a file that does not exist. Compare with sysErrPermissionDenied.
B_ENTRY_EXISTS  You have attempted to perform an operation that would create an entry with a specific name, where there is already such an entry.
B_NAME_TOO_LONG 
B_OUT_OF_RANGE

INLINE_FNC int cmpxchg32 (  volatile int32_t *  atom,
int32_t *  value,
int32_t  newValue
) 
 

Perform a 32-bit atomic compare and swap.

If the current value of *atom is the same as the current value of *value, atomically sets *atom to newValue and returns TRUE. Otherwise, sets *value to the current value of *atom and returns FALSE.

INLINE_FNC int cmpxchg64 (  volatile int64_t *  atom,
int64_t *  value,
int64_t  newValue
) 
 

Perform a 64-bit atomic compare and swap.

If the current value of *atom is the same as the current value of *value, atomically sets *atom to newValue and returns TRUE. Otherwise, sets *value to the current value of *atom and returns FALSE.

void* inplace_realloc (  void *  ,
size_t 
) 
 

Perform a realloc, but only if it won't change the location of the memory.

This function is needed by some parts of the Support Kit. If your platform doesn't have it, you can just implement it to return NULL.

Note:
In the Rome branch, this is an inline function here, while in other branches it is implemented in WindowsComaptibility.cpp and LinuxCompat.cpp. The latter is probably more correct.
